</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub38.ezboard.com/ushuyung.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Shuyung</A> at: 2/12/02 6:06:48 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccccc><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub38.ezboard.com/ueveel.showPublicProfile?language=EN>eveel</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Monk-in-Training</span><br>  Posts: 61<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(2/13/02 5:06:03 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=474.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Why do I get this ?</span><hr size=1> Primary hand delay has no-effect whatsoever on secondary delay. To prove this, equip a non-weapon in your primary hand and just attack with the off hand. If there were any correlation between the two hands then the secondary would never attack.<br>
<br>
Basically, the equations you're looking for are:-<br>
<br>
Modal primary-hand damage + double attack likelihood = total primary hand damage.<br>
(Modal off-hand damage * dualwield likelihood) + double attack likelihood = total off-hand damage.<br>
<br>
Treat the two as seperate entities and add the damage together at the end.<br>
<br>
